block content

  +state('New York', '/assets/images/flag-new-york.svg', 'The Empire State', 'July 26, 1788')

  .intro
    p The New York flag, one of unusually wide proportion, follows a common pattern for U.S. state flags, featuring the state coat of arms on a field of blue.
    p It spotlights many images seen in other state seals and flags like the goddess Liberty, Phrygian cap, and bald eagle, among others.
    p An original version of the flag was adopted in 1788, but the current iteration was officially adopted April 2, 1901.

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Flag design
      p The flag of New York features a field of deep blue with the state coat of arms placed at the center. Prominent are two supporters, the goddesses Liberty and Justice.
    .visual.flag
      img(src='/assets/images/flag-new-york.svg')

  .guide.wide
    .content
      h2 Iconography
      ul.visual.icon-list
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-new-york-icon-liberty.svg')
          h4 Liberty
          p The goddess Liberty represents freedom (fitting for New York, home to the Statue of Liberty).
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-new-york-icon-justice.svg')
          h4 Justice
          p The blindfolded goddess Justice stands with sword ready to fight tyranny.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-new-york-icon-cap.svg')
          h4 Phrygian cap
          p The Phrygian cap, borrowed iconography from the French Revolution, represents liberty.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-new-york-icon-crown.svg')
          h4 Crown
          p Liberty has a crown underfoot, a symbol of freedom from England after the Revolutionary War.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-new-york-icon-scales.svg')
          h4 Scales
          p The goddess Justice holds the scales which symbolize justice and equality under the law.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-new-york-icon-eagle.svg')
          h4 Eagle & globe
          p The globe shows both Europe and the Americas and represents the meeting of two worlds. The eagle faces west toward the New World.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-new-york-icon-hudson.svg')
          h4 Hudson River
          p A sun rises above ships navigating the Hudson river, representing New York’s natural beauty and commerce by waterway.
        li.icon-item
          span.icon: img(src='/assets/images/flag-new-york-icon-excelsior.svg')
          h4 Excelsior
          p The Latin word “Excelsior” translates to “Ever Upward,” New York’s state motto and attitude toward progress.

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Coat of Arms
      p The New York coat of arms was originally designed in 1777 and officially adopted on March 16th, 1778 (a few months before statehood).
      p A commission was appointed in 1880 to standardize its presentation.
    .visual.flag
      img(src='/assets/images/coat-of-arms-new-york.jpg')

  .guide
    .content
      h2 Colors
      p The prominent color is a deep blue, with supporting colors within the coat of arms.
